1002 Olbersia.label: 1002 Olbersia
1002 Olbersia.description: 1002 Olbersia is a main-belt asteroid. It was discovered by Vladimir Aleksandrovich Albitzky on August 15, 1923. It was named after Heinrich Wilhelm Matthias Olbers. Wikipedia

106 Dione.label: 106 Dione
106 Dione.description: 106 Dione is a large main-belt asteroid. It probably has a composition similar to 1 Ceres. It was discovered by J. C. Watson on October 10, 1868, and named after Dione, a Titaness in Greek mythology ... Wikipedia

108 Hecuba.label: 108 Hecuba
108 Hecuba.description: 108 Hecuba is a fairly large and bright main-belt asteroid. It was discovered by Karl Theodor Robert Luther on April 2, 1869, and named after Hecuba, wife of King Priam in the legends of the Trojan War in Greek Mythology. Wikipedia

1136 Mercedes.label: 1136 Mercedes
1136 Mercedes.description: 1136 Mercedes is a main belt asteroid orbiting the Sun. Approximately 25 kilometers in diameter, it makes a revolution around the Sun once every 4 years. It was discovered by Josep Comas Solá on October 30, 1929 in Barcelona, Spain. Wikipedia

113 Amalthea.label: 113 Amalthea
113 Amalthea.description: 113 Amalthea is a fairly typical rocky main-belt asteroid orbiting in the inner regions of the belt. It was discovered by R. Luther on March 12, 1871. The name comes from Amalthea of Greek mythology. Wikipedia

115 Thyra.label: 115 Thyra
115 Thyra.description: 115 Thyra is a fairly large and bright inner main-belt asteroid that was discovered by Canadian-American astronomer J. C. Watson on August 6, 1871 and was named for Thyra, the consort of King Gorm the Old of Denmark. Wikipedia

116 Sirona.label: 116 Sirona
116 Sirona.description: 116 Sirona is a somewhat large and bright-colored main-belt asteroid that was discovered by the German-American astronomer C. H. F. Peters on September 8, 1871, and named after Sirona, the Celtic goddess of healing. Wikipedia

117 Lomia.label: 117 Lomia
117 Lomia.description: 117 Lomia is a large main-belt asteroid that has a nearly circular orbit; the orbital eccentricity is 0.029. It was discovered by French astronomer Alphonse Borrelly on September 12, 1871 from the Marseilles Observatory. Wikipedia

118 Peitho.label: 118 Peitho
118 Peitho.description: 118 Peitho is a main-belt asteroid. It is probably an S-type asteroid. It was discovered by R. Luther on March 15, 1872, and named after one of the two Peithos in Greek mythology. Wikipedia

1221 Amor.label: 1221 Amor
1221 Amor.description: 1221 Amor is the namesake of the Amor asteroids, a group of near-Earth asteroids whose orbits range between those of Earth and Mars. Amors are often Mars-crossers but they are not Earth-crossers. Wikipedia

122 Gerda.label: 122 Gerda
122 Gerda.description: 122 Gerda is a fairly large outer main-belt asteroid that was discovered by German-American astronomer C. H. F. Peters on July 31, 1872, and named after Gerðr, the wife of the god Freyr in Norse mythology. Wikipedia

132 Aethra.label: 132 Aethra
132 Aethra.description: 132 Aethra is an M-type main-belt asteroid. It has a rather eccentric orbit that sometimes brings it closer to the Sun than the planet Mars. Wikipedia

133 Cyrene.label: 133 Cyrene
133 Cyrene.description: 133 Cyrene is a fairly large and very bright main-belt asteroid that was discovered by J. C. Watson on August 16, 1873, and named after Cyrene, a nymph, daughter of king Hypseus and beloved of Apollo in Greek mythology. Wikipedia

135 Hertha.label: 135 Hertha
135 Hertha.description: 135 Hertha is a large main-belt asteroid. Named Hertha, another name for Nerthus, a Germanic fertility goddess. Wikipedia

141 Lumen.label: 141 Lumen
141 Lumen.description: 141 Lumen is a dark, large rocky asteroid 130 km in diameter orbiting in the main belt near the Eunomia family of asteroids. It is not, however, physically related to the group, being of the wrong spectral class. Wikipedia

138 Tolosa.label: 138 Tolosa
138 Tolosa.description: 138 Tolosa is a brightly coloured, stony main-belt asteroid. It was discovered by French astronomer Henri Joseph Perrotin on May 19, 1874, and named after the Latin name for Toulouse, France. Wikipedia

145 Adeona.label: 145 Adeona
145 Adeona.description: 145 Adeona is a rather large main-belt asteroid. Its surface is very dark, and, based upon its classification as a C-type asteroid, is probably composed of primitive carbonaceous material. The Adeona family of asteroids is named after it. Wikipedia

148 Gallia.label: 148 Gallia
148 Gallia.description: 148 Gallia is a large main-belt asteroid that is named after the Latin name for France Gaul. Gallia was discovered by the French brothers Paul Henry and Prosper Henry on August 7, 1875, but the credit for this discovery was given to Prosper. Wikipedia

15761 Schumi.label: 15761 Schumi
15761 Schumi.description: 15761 Schumi is a main-belt asteroid discovered on September 24, 1992 by L. D. Schmadel and F. Borngen at Tautenburg. Wikipedia

1580 Betulia.label: 1580 Betulia
1580 Betulia.description: 1580 Betulia is an Amor asteroid discovered on May 22, 1950 by Ernest Leonard Johnson at the Union Observatory, Johannesburg, South Africa. Wikipedia

1627 Ivar.label: 1627 Ivar
1627 Ivar.description: 1627 Ivar is a large Mars-crosser asteroid that was discovered in 1929 by Ejnar Hertzsprung at the Union Observatory in Johannesburg, South Africa. Wikipedia

162 Laurentia.label: 162 Laurentia
162 Laurentia.description: 162 Laurentia is a large and dark main-belt asteroid that was discovered by the French brothers Paul Henry and Prosper Henry on April 21, 1876, and named after A. Laurent, an amateur astronomer who discovered asteroid 51 Nemausa. Wikipedia

1685 Toro.label: 1685 Toro
1685 Toro.description: 1685 Toro is an Apollo asteroid that orbits the Sun in an 58 resonance with Earth, and a near 513 resonance with Venus. Because of this unusual orbit, it is sometimes referenced as "Earth's second satellite". Wikipedia

1691 Oort.label: 1691 Oort
1691 Oort.description: 1691 Oort is a main-belt asteroid discovered on September 9, 1956 by Ingrid van Houten-Groeneveld and Karl Wilhelm Reinmuth at Heidelberg. It was named after the Dutch astronomer Jan Oort. Wikipedia

1796 Riga.label: 1796 Riga
1796 Riga.description: 1796 Riga is an outer main-belt asteroid discovered on May 16, 1966 by N. Chernykh at Nauchnyj. Wikipedia

1807 Slovakia.label: 1807 Slovakia
1807 Slovakia.description: 1807 Slovakia is a main-belt asteroid discovered on August 20, 1971 by M. Antal at Skalnaté Pleso Observatory. Wikipedia

1917 Cuyo.label: 1917 Cuyo
1917 Cuyo.description:
1917 Cuyo is an Amor asteroid discovered on January 1, 1968 by Carlos Ulrrico Cesco and Samuel, A. at El Leoncito.
In 1989, this object was detected with radar from the Arecibo Observatory at a distance of 0.17 AU. Wikipedia

1981 Midas.label: 1981 Midas
1981 Midas.description: The asteroid 1981 Midas was discovered on March 6, 1973 by Charles T. Kowal at Palomar Observatory. It is named after Midas, the king of Phrygia in Greek mythology who turned objects to gold when he touched them. Wikipedia

197 Arete.label: 197 Arete
197 Arete.description:
197 Arete is an asteroid in the asteroid belt. It has a very bright surface, unusually bright even for a rocky S-type asteroid.
It was discovered by J. Palisa on May 21, 1879, and named after Arete, the mother of Nausicaa in Homer's The Odyssey. Wikipedia

2001 QR322.label: 2001 QR322
2001 QR322.description:
2001 QR322 was the first Neptune trojan discovered, in 2001 by the Deep Ecliptic Survey. It orbits ahead of Neptune at its L4 Lagrangian point.
With an absolute magnitude of 7.8 to 8.2, it has a diameter in the range of 60 to 160 km. Wikipedia

2002 AA29.label: 2002 AA29
2002 AA29.description: 2002 AA29 is a small near-Earth asteroid that was discovered on January 9, 2002 by the LINEAR automatic sky survey. The diameter of the asteroid is only about 50 to 110 metres. Wikipedia

2002 Euler.label: 2002 Euler
2002 Euler.description: 2002 Euler is an asteroid named after the Swiss mathematician and physicist Leonhard Euler. The asteroid was discovered on August 29, 1973, by Tamara Mikhailovna Smirnova. Wikipedia

2003 YN107.label: 2003 YN107
2003 YN107.description: 2003 YN107, also written 2003 YN107, is a very small near-Earth object moving in a 11 mean motion resonance with the Earth. As such it is co-orbital to Earth. Wikipedia

2004 XP14.label: 2004 XP14
2004 XP14.description:
2004 XP14 is a near-Earth asteroid, first discovered on December 10, 2004, by the LINEAR project.
Due to the proximity of its orbit to Earth and its estimated size, this object has been classified as ... Wikipedia

2006 HZ51.label: 2006 HZ51
2006 HZ51.description: 2006 HZ51 is an 800 m diameter asteroid discovered on 27 April 2006 by the Catalina Sky Survey that was thought to have a chance of hitting Earth on 21 June 2008. Further refinement of its orbit eliminated this risk. Wikipedia

201 Penelope.label: 201 Penelope
201 Penelope.description: 201 Penelope is a large main belt asteroid that was discovered by Austrian astronomer Johann Palisa on August 7, 1879 in Pola. The asteroid is named after Penelope, the wife of Odysseus in Homer's The Odyssey. Wikipedia

204 Kallisto.label: 204 Kallisto
204 Kallisto.description:
204 Kallisto is a fairly typical, although sizeable Main belt asteroid. It is classified as an S-type asteroid. Like other asteroids of its type, it is light in colour.
It was discovered by Johann Palisa on October 8, 1879 in Pola. Wikipedia

205 Martha.label: 205 Martha
205 Martha.description:
205 Martha is a large Main belt asteroid. It is a dark, primitive carbonaceous C-type asteroid.
It was discovered by Johann Palisa on October 13, 1879 in Pola and was named after Martha, a woman in the New Testament. Wikipedia

2061 Anza.label: 2061 Anza
2061 Anza.description: 2061 Anza is an Amor asteroid discovered on October 22, 1960 by Henry L. Giclas at Flagstaff. Wikipedia

2062 Aten.label: 2062 Aten
2062 Aten.description: 2062 Aten is an asteroid that was discovered at the Palomar Mountain Observatory by Eleanor F. Helin, who is now the principal scientist for the NEAT project. It is named after Aten, the Egyptian god of the solar disk. Wikipedia

2063 Bacchus.label: 2063 Bacchus
2063 Bacchus.description: 2063 Bacchus is an Apollo asteroid and Venus- and Mars-crosser asteroid. It was discovered on April 24, 1977, by Charles T. Kowal at the Palomar Observatory. Wikipedia

206 Hersilia.label: 206 Hersilia
206 Hersilia.description: 206 Hersilia is a fairly large Main belt asteroid. It was discovered by C. H. F. Peters on October 13, 1879 in Clinton, New York. The asteroid was named after Hersilia, Roman wife of Romulus. Wikipedia

207 Hedda.label: 207 Hedda
207 Hedda.description: 207 Hedda is a sizeable Main belt asteroid. It is a C-type asteroid, meaning it is primitive in composition and dark in colour. Wikipedia

211 Isolda.label: 211 Isolda
211 Isolda.description: 211 Isolda is a very large, dark main-belt asteroid. It is classified as a C-type asteroid and is probably composed of primitive carbonaceous material. Wikipedia

213 Lilaea.label: 213 Lilaea
213 Lilaea.description: 213 Lilaea is a large main belt asteroid. It was discovered by German-American astronomer C. H. F. Peters on February 16, 1880 in Clinton, New York and was named after Lilaea, a Naiad in Greek mythology. Wikipedia

215 Oenone.label: 215 Oenone
215 Oenone.description:
215 Oenone is a typical Main belt asteroid.
It was discovered by Viktor Knorre on April 7, 1880 in Berlin. It was the second of his four asteroid discoveries.
It was named after Oenone, a nymph in Greek mythology. Wikipedia

216 Kleopatra.label: 216 Kleopatra
216 Kleopatra.description: 216 Kleopatra is a main-belt asteroid that was discovered by Austrian astronomer Johann Palisa on April 10, 1880, from Pula. It is named after Cleopatra, the famous queen of Ancient Egypt. Wikipedia

217 Eudora.label: 217 Eudora
217 Eudora.description: 217 Eudora is a large Main belt asteroid. It was discovered by French astronomer J. Coggia on August 30, 1880 in Marseilles, France. It was his fourth asteroid discovery and is named after Eudora, a Hyad in Greek mythology. Wikipedia

218 Bianca.label: 218 Bianca
218 Bianca.description:
218 Bianca is a sizeable Main belt asteroid. It is an S-type asteroid.
It was discovered by Johann Palisa on September 4, 1880, in Pola and was named after the Austro-Hungarian opera singer Bianca Bianchi. Wikipedia

2202 Pele.label: 2202 Pele
2202 Pele.description: 2202 Pele is an asteroid. It is a Mars-crosser asteroid, that is, this type of asteroid's orbit crosses the orbit of Mars. It is an Amor asteroid, that is, this type of asteroid approaches the orbit of Earth from beyond, but does not cross it. Wikipedia

222 Lucia.label: 222 Lucia
222 Lucia.description: 222 Lucia is a large Themistian asteroid. It is spectral C-type and is probably composed of primitive carbonaceous material. Wikipedia

224 Oceana.label: 224 Oceana
224 Oceana.description: 224 Oceana is a sizeable main belt asteroid that was discovered byAustrian astronomer Johann Palisa on March 30, 1882 in Vienna. It was named after the Pacific Ocean. Wikipedia

225 Henrietta.label: 225 Henrietta
225 Henrietta.description: 225 Henrietta is a very large outer main-belt asteroid. It was discovered by Johann Palisa on April 19, 1882, in Vienna and named after Henrietta, wife of astronomer Pierre J. C. Janssen. Wikipedia

230 Athamantis.label: 230 Athamantis
230 Athamantis.description: 230 Athamantis is a fairly large main-belt asteroid that was discovered by the German-Austrian astronomer K. de Ball on September 3, 1882, in Bothkamp. It was his only asteroid discovery. Wikipedia

232 Russia.label: 232 Russia
232 Russia.description: 232 Russia is a large Main belt asteroid. It is classified as a C-type asteroid and is probably composed of primitive carbonaceous material. It was discovered by Johann Palisa on January 31, 1883 in Vienna and was named after the country of Russia. Wikipedia

241 Germania.label: 241 Germania
241 Germania.description:
241 Germania is a very large main-belt asteroid. It is classified as a C-type asteroid and is probably composed of dark, privitive carbonaceous material.
It was discovered by Robert Luther on September 12, 1884 in Düsseldorf. Wikipedia

246 Asporina.label: 246 Asporina
246 Asporina.description:
246 Asporina is a sizeable Main belt asteroid. It is classified as one of the few R-type asteroids.
It was discovered by A. Borrelly on March 6, 1885 in Marseilles and was named after Asporina, a goddess worshipped in Asia Minor. Wikipedia

248 Lameia.label: 248 Lameia
248 Lameia.description:
248 Lameia is a quite typical Main belt asteroid.
It was discovered by Johann Palisa on June 5, 1885 in Vienna and was named after Lamia, a lover of Zeus. Wikipedia

251 Sophia.label: 251 Sophia
251 Sophia.description:
251 Sophia is a main belt asteroid.
It was discovered by Johann Palisa on October 4, 1885 in Vienna and was named after Sophia, wife of astronomer Hugo von Seeliger. Wikipedia

252 Clementina.label: 252 Clementina
252 Clementina.description: 252 Clementina is a large main belt asteroid that was discovered by French astronomer Henri Joseph Anastase Perrotin on October 11, 1885 in Nice, France. The origin of the name is not certain, but is believed to be the name of Perrotin's first cat. Wikipedia

2552 Remek.label: 2552 Remek
2552 Remek.description: 2552 Remek is a main-belt asteroid discovered on September 24, 1978 by Antonín Mrkos at Kleť Observatory and named after Czechoslovak cosmonaut Vladimír Remek. Wikipedia

258 Tyche.label: 258 Tyche
258 Tyche.description: 258 Tyche is a relatively large main belt asteroid discovered in 1886. It is classified as an S-type. Tyche orbits very close to the Eunomia family of asteroids, and could be a member based on composition. Wikipedia

261 Prymno.label: 261 Prymno
261 Prymno.description: 261 Prymno is a somewhat large Main belt asteroid. It is classified as a B-type asteroid and probably has a primitive composition not unlike common C-type carbonaceous asteroids. Wikipedia

262 Valda.label: 262 Valda
262 Valda.description: 262 Valda is a main belt asteroid that was discovered by Austrian astronomer Johann Palisa on November 3, 1886 in Vienna. The origin of the name is unknown. Wikipedia

263 Dresda.label: 263 Dresda
263 Dresda.description:
263 Dresda is a typical Main belt asteroid. It belongs to the Koronis family of asteroids.
It has a lightly coloured surface and likely is not composed of carbonaceus materials, but is similar in ... Wikipedia

267 Tirza.label: 267 Tirza
267 Tirza.description:
267 Tirza is a fairly sizeable, very dark Main belt asteroid.
It was discovered by Auguste Charlois on May 27, 1887 in Nice. It was his first asteroid discovery.
It was named after Tirzah, a woman in the Bible. Wikipedia

268 Adorea.label: 268 Adorea
268 Adorea.description:
268 Adorea is a very large Themistian asteroid. It is classified as a primitive carbonaceous F-type/C-type asteroid.
It was discovered by A. Borrelly on June 8, 1887 in Marseilles. Wikipedia

2740 Tsoj.label: 2740 Tsoj
2740 Tsoj.description:
2740 Tsoj is a main-belt asteroid discovered on September 26, 1974 by L. Zhuravleva at Nauchnyj.
Named in memory of Viktor Tsoi, poet, composer, and soloist of the Soviet rock-group Kino. Wikipedia

274 Philagoria.label: 274 Philagoria
274 Philagoria.description:
274 Philagoria is a typical Main belt asteroid.
It was discovered by Johann Palisa on April 3, 1888 in Vienna. Wikipedia

277 Elvira.label: 277 Elvira
277 Elvira.description: 277 Elvira is a typical main belt asteroid and is a member of the Koronis asteroid family. It was discovered by Auguste Charlois on May 3, 1888 in Nice. Wikipedia

279 Thule.label: 279 Thule
279 Thule.description:
279 Thule is a large asteroid from the asteroid belt. It is classified as a D-type asteroid and is probably composed of organic-rich silicates, carbon and anhydrous silicates.
The orbit of Thule is unusual. Wikipedia

280 Philia.label: 280 Philia
280 Philia.description:
280 Philia is a fairly large Main belt asteroid.
It was discovered by Johann Palisa on October 29, 1888 at the Vienna Observatory. Wikipedia

281 Lucretia.label: 281 Lucretia
281 Lucretia.description:
281 Lucretia is an asteroid belonging to the Flora family in the Main Belt.
It was discovered by Johann Palisa on October 31, 1888 in Vienna. It is named for the middle name of Caroline Herschel, one of the first female astronomers. Wikipedia

282 Clorinde.label: 282 Clorinde
282 Clorinde.description:
282 Clorinde is a typical Main belt asteroid.
It was discovered by Auguste Charlois on January 28, 1889 in Nice. Wikipedia

285 Regina.label: 285 Regina
285 Regina.description:
285 Regina is typical, although fairly large Main belt asteroid.
It was discovered by Auguste Charlois on August 3, 1889 in Nice. Wikipedia

286 Iclea.label: 286 Iclea
286 Iclea.description:
286 Iclea is a large Main belt asteroid.
It was discovered by Johann Palisa on August 3, 1889 in Vienna. Wikipedia

287 Nephthys.label: 287 Nephthys
287 Nephthys.description: 287 Nephthys is a large Main belt asteroid that was discovered by German-American astronomer C. H. F. Peters on August 25, 1889 in Clinton, New York and named after Nephthys in Egyptian mythology. It is classified as an S-type asteroid. Wikipedia

288 Glauke.label: 288 Glauke
288 Glauke.description: 288 Glauke is an asteroid from the asteroid belt discovered by Robert Luther in 1890. It was the last of his asteroid discoveries. It is named after Glauke, a daughter of Creon a king of Corinth in Greek mythology. Wikipedia

2893 Peiroos.label: 2893 Peiroos
2893 Peiroos.description: 2893 Peiroos is a Jupiter Trojan discovered on August 30, 1975 by Felix Aguilar Observatory at El Leoncito. Wikipedia

290 Bruna.label: 290 Bruna
290 Bruna.description: 290 Bruna is a main belt asteroid that was discovered on March 20, 1890 by Johann Palisa, an Austrian astronomer at the Vienna Observatory. Wikipedia

29227 Wegener.label: 29227 Wegener
29227 Wegener.description:
29227 Wegener is a main-belt asteroid discovered on February 29, 1992 by F. Borngen at Tautenburg.
It was named after the German geophysicist, polar researcher and meteorologist Alfred Wegener, originator of the theory of Plate tectonics. Wikipedia

296 Phaëtusa.label: 296 Phaëtusa
296 Phaëtusa.description:
296 Phaëtusa is a small Main belt asteroid.
It was discovered by Auguste Charlois on August 19, 1890 in Nice. Wikipedia

299 Thora.label: 299 Thora
299 Thora.description:
299 Thora is a typical Main belt asteroid.
It was discovered by Johann Palisa on October 6, 1890 in Vienna. Wikipedia

3001 Michelangelo.label: 3001 Michelangelo
3001 Michelangelo.description:
3001 Michelangelo is a small main belt asteroid, which was discovered by Edward L. G. Bowell in 1982. It is named after Michelangelo Buonarroti, the Italian renaissance artist.
Michelangelo's closest approaches to Mars are just over 0.6 AU. Wikipedia

306 Unitas.label: 306 Unitas
306 Unitas.description: 306 Unitas is a typical main belt asteroid that was discovered by Elia Millosevich on March 1, 1891 in Rome. The asteroid was named by the director of the Modena Observatory in honor of the Italian astronomer Angelo Secchi. Wikipedia

308 Polyxo.label: 308 Polyxo
308 Polyxo.description: 308 Polyxo is a main-belt asteroid that was discovered by A. Borrelly on March 31, 1891, in Marseilles. It is classified as a rare T-type asteroid. Wikipedia

3103 Eger.label: 3103 Eger
3103 Eger.description:
3103 Eger is an Apollo and Mars-crosser asteroid that was discovered in 1982, by Miklós Lovas. It was named after the city of Eger, Hungary.
It makes eight approaches to Earth less than 30 Gm in the 20th and 21st centuries. Wikipedia

311 Claudia.label: 311 Claudia
311 Claudia.description:
311 Claudia is a typical Main belt asteroid.
It was discovered by Auguste Charlois on June 11, 1891 in Nice. The name was suggested to Charlois by the amateur astronomer Arthur Mee of Cardiff, Wales, to commemorate Mee's wife, Claudia. Wikipedia

315 Constantia.label: 315 Constantia
315 Constantia.description:
315 Constantia is a small asteroid belonging to the Flora family in the Main Belt.
It was discovered by Johann Palisa on September 4, 1891 in Vienna. Wikipedia

316 Goberta.label: 316 Goberta
316 Goberta.description: 316 Goberta is a mid-sized Themistian asteroid that was discovered by French astronomer Auguste Charlois on September 8, 1891 in Nice, France. Wikipedia

317 Roxane.label: 317 Roxane
317 Roxane.description: 317 Roxane is a main belt asteroid, about 19km in diameter. It was discovered by Auguste Charlois from Nice on September 11, 1891. Wikipedia
